because he overlooked the increase in path length in the rest frame of the aether. This was corrected by Alfred Potier (1882) and Hendrik Lorentz (1886). The derivation in the transverse direction can be given as follows (analogous to the derivation of time dilation using a light clock): The beam is propagating at the speed of light formula_1 and hits the mirror at time formula_17, traveling the distance formula_18. At the same time, the mirror has traveled the distance formula_19 in the &quot;x&quot; direction. So in order to hit the mirror, the travel path of the beam is formula_3 in the &quot;y&quot; direction (assuming equal-length arms) and formula_19 in the &quot;x&quot; direction. This inclined travel path follows from the transformation from the interferometer rest frame to the aether rest frame. Therefore, the Pythagorean theorem gives the actual beam travel distance of formula_22. Thus formula_23 and consequently the travel time formula_24, which is the same for the backward journey. The total travel time formula_25 is:

:formula_26

